---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import TitleHeader from "../components/TitleHeader.astro";
import { shortlisted } from "../lib/dataset-catalog";
---

<BaseLayout title="FAQ — Japanese Word Rank Lookup">
  <TitleHeader />
  <main class="page-content max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pt-18 pb-16">
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6">FAQ</h1>

    <h2 class="text-lg font-bold mb-4">Word Card Tier Emoji</h2>

    <h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What is the emoji at the top-right of each word card?</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-4">
      Each word card shows a tier emoji indicating how common that word is across Japanese language sources. It gives you a quick sense of how frequently the word appears in real Japanese — basic everyday words vs. advanced vocabulary.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What does each emoji mean?</h3>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm text-muted-foreground border-collapse">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-border">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-bold text-foreground">Emoji</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-bold text-foreground">Tier</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 font-bold text-foreground">Rank Range</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-border">
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">🌱</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">BASIC</td><td class="py-2">1 – 1,800</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">☘️</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">COMMON</td><td class="py-2">1,801 – 5,000</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">🌷</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">FLUENT</td><td class="py-2">5,001 – 12,000</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">📚</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">ADVANCED</td><td class="py-2">12,001 – 25,000</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">🦉</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">UNRANKED</td><td class="py-2">Not ranked / rare</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How is the tier computed?</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
      The tier uses a <strong class="text-foreground">bucket count algorithm</strong> across a selected list of Japanese frequency datasets (subtitles, web text, spoken corpora, Wikipedia, etc.). For each word:
    </p>
    <ol class="list-decimal list-inside text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3 space-y-1">
      <li>Collect the word's rank from each dataset (ignore datasets where the word is absent).</li>
      <li>If the word appears in fewer than 3 datasets, it is marked <strong class="text-foreground">UNRANKED</strong>.</li>
      <li>Count how many dataset ranks fall into each tier bucket (BASIC, COMMON, FLUENT, ADVANCED).</li>
      <li>Assign the tier with the most counts. On a tie, the higher tier wins.</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-6">
      This means a word reaches 🌱 BASIC only if <em>most</em> sources agree it is very common — not just one. It is a majority-vote across sources, making it more conservative than a simple minimum-rank approach.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What are the selected datasets used?</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-8 space-y-1">
      {shortlisted.map((dataset) => (
        <li>
          {dataset.source && (
            <span class="font-medium text-foreground/70">{dataset.source}: </span>
          )}
          {dataset.description}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-lg font-bold mb-4">Duplicate Entries</h2>

    <h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Why do some words have duplicate entries?</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
      Some words appear more than once because the underlying dataset contains separate entries for the <strong class="text-foreground">kanji form</strong> and the <strong class="text-foreground">kana-only form</strong> of the same word. For example, <span lang="ja">食べる</span> and <span lang="ja">たべる</span> each have their own row with their own frequency ranks — even though they represent the same word.
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
      Automatically merging these is surprisingly difficult:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3 space-y-1">
      <li><strong class="text-foreground">Same reading ≠ same word.</strong> <span lang="ja">する</span> (to do), <span lang="ja">刷る</span> (to print), and <span lang="ja">擦る</span> (to rub) all read <span lang="ja">する</span> but are completely different words.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-foreground">One-to-many matches.</strong> The kana <span lang="ja">いる</span> could correspond to <span lang="ja">居る</span>, <span lang="ja">炒る</span>, <span lang="ja">要る</span>, or <span lang="ja">射る</span>.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-foreground">Function words overlap.</strong> <span lang="ja">ます</span> (polite suffix) and <span lang="ja">増す</span> (to increase) share a reading but are not the same word.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-8">
      Rather than risk incorrect merges, we keep both entries so you can see the original frequency data for each form as it appears in the source dataset.
    </p>

    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">
      For full details see <a href="https://github.com/PikaPikaGems/japanese-word-frequency" class="underline hover:text-foreground">PikaPikaGems/japanese-word-frequency</a>.
    </p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
